  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and regulations aimed at preventing money laundering. Some key examples include:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) - An intergovernmental organization that sets global standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\n2. United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime - Provides a framework for international cooperation in fighting money laundering.\n\n3. The Wolfsberg Principles - A set of guidelines developed by major international banks to prevent financial crimes.\n\n4. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision - Provides recommendations for preventing money laundering in the banking sector.\n\n5. International monetary regulations like the Bank Secrecy Act (in the US) and similar laws in the EU require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions and conduct due diligence on customers.\n\nThese laws typically require financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Monitor and report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain records\n- Implement anti-money laundering (AML) compliance programs\n\nMost countries have their own national laws that implement these international standards and guidelines.",
